Edition:
Quote: They are divided into two classes, viz.,<i> ranghateeroos</i> (or chiefs) and their relations of different degrees of consanguinity, and <i>cookees</i> (slaves), who are nearly black, and much shorter, and appear a different race of people.
Notes: 1829 Mar 2 Atkins's Narrative in 1908 McNab Historical Records 1/696

Date: 0/0/1830
Source: New Zealanders, The
Author: CRAIK
Vol / Page: 52fn
Edition:
Quote: <i>Cookee</i> ... is the term generally used for a slave, in recent accounts of New Zealand; but it does not appear whether it is a native word or a formation from the English `cook' - a profession which the New Zealanders hold in greatest comtempt and look upon as only for slaves. <i>Ibid.</i> 236 ... when cookees die they perish for ever .
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1834
